name: Cerebral Cortex
description: The cerebral cortex is the outermost layer of the brain, and it is responsible for many of our higher-level functions, such as thinking, feeling, and perceiving. It is made up of gray matter, which is composed of densely packed neurons. The cerebral cortex is divided into four lobes: the frontal lobe, the parietal lobe, the temporal lobe, and the occipital lobe. Each lobe is responsible for different functions.

name: Primary Visual Cortex
description: The primary visual cortex, also known as V1, is the first area of the brain to receive visual information from the retina. It is located in the occipital lobe at the back of the brain. V1 is responsible for processing the basic features of vision, such as shape, color, and movement.

name: Medial Geniculate Nucleus
description: The medial geniculate nucleus (MGN) is a part of the thalamus, which is a relay station for sensory information traveling to the cortex. The MGN is responsible for relaying auditory information from the inferior colliculus to the primary auditory cortex.

name: Hypothalamus
description:
The hypothalamus is a small, pea-sized structure located at the base of the brain. It is responsible for a wide range of functions, including:

* **Body temperature regulation:** The hypothalamus controls the release of hormones that help regulate body temperature.
* **Appetite and weight control:** The hypothalamus controls the release of hormones that regulate appetite and weight.
* **Water balance:** The hypothalamus controls the release of hormones that regulate water balance.
* **Sleep-wake cycle:** The hypothalamus controls the release of hormones that regulate the sleep-wake cycle.
* **Reproduction:** The hypothalamus controls the release of hormones that regulate reproduction.

name: Premotor Cortex
description: The premotor cortex is a region of the brain that is involved in planning and executing voluntary movements. It is located in front of the primary motor cortex, which is responsible for actually carrying out movements. The premotor cortex receives input from sensory areas of the brain, as well as from other parts of the brain that are involved in cognition and emotion.

name: Optic Radiation
description: The optic radiation is a bundle of nerve fibers that carries visual information from the lateral geniculate nucleus (LGN) to the primary visual cortex (V1) in the occipital lobe. It is located in the white matter of the brain, and it is made up of millions of nerve fibers.

name: Anterior Nucleus
description:
The anterior nucleus (AN) is a group of nuclei in the thalamus, a structure deep in the brain. The AN is involved in a variety of functions, including:

* **Motivation:** The AN is involved in the motivation to seek rewards and avoid punishments.
* **Memory:** The AN is involved in the consolidation of new memories.
* **Emotion:** The AN is involved in the processing of emotions, such as pleasure and pain.
* **Pain:** The AN is involved in the modulation of pain.

name: Red Nucleus
description: The red nucleus is a small, oval-shaped structure located in the midbrain. It is part of the extrapyramidal system, which is a network of brain structures that control movement. The red nucleus receives input from the cerebellum and the basal ganglia, and it sends output to the spinal cord.

name: Parietooccipital Sulcus
description:
The parietooccipital sulcus is a deep sulcus in the cerebral cortex that marks the boundary between the cuneus and precuneus, and also between the parietal and occipital lobes. It is a landmark structure in the brain, and it is involved in a number of functions, including:

* **Visual processing:** The parietooccipital sulcus is involved in the processing of visual information, such as shape, color, and movement.
* **Spatial awareness:** The parietooccipital sulcus is involved in spatial awareness, such as the ability to know where your body is in space.
* **Attention:** The parietooccipital sulcus is involved in attention, such as the ability to focus on a particular object or task.

name: Thalamus
description: The thalamus is a large, egg-shaped structure located in the middle of the brain. It is a relay station for sensory information traveling to the cortex. The thalamus receives input from all of the senses, including vision, hearing, touch, taste, and smell. It then sends this information to the appropriate areas of the cortex for further processing.

name: Longitudinal Fissure
description: The longitudinal fissure is a deep fissure that divides the cerebrum into two hemispheres, the left and right hemispheres. It is the largest fissure in the brain, and it runs from the front of the brain to the back. The longitudinal fissure contains the corpus callosum, a large bundle of nerve fibers that connects the two hemispheres.

name: Mammilary Body
description: The mammillary bodies are a pair of small, oval-shaped structures located in the hypothalamus, a part of the brain that is involved in a variety of functions, including memory, olfaction, and emotions. The mammillary bodies receive input from the hippocampus, a region of the brain that is involved in memory, and they send output to the anterior thalamus, a region of the brain that is involved in olfaction.

name: Postcentral Gyrus
description: The postcentral gyrus is a strip of cortex located in the parietal lobe of the brain. It is responsible for processing somatosensory information, which is information about the body's position and movement. The postcentral gyrus receives input from the thalamus, a structure deep in the brain that relays sensory information from the body to the cortex.

name: Central Sulcus
description: The central sulcus, also known as the fissure of Rolando, is a deep groove that divides the frontal lobe from the parietal lobe in the brain. It is one of the most prominent features of the cerebral cortex, and it is important for motor and sensory processing.

name: Dorsomedial Nucleus
description:
The dorsomedial nucleus (DMN) is a group of neurons located in the thalamus, a structure deep in the brain. The DMN is involved in a variety of functions, including:

* **Memory:** The DMN is involved in the consolidation of memories, which is the process of storing memories in the brain.
* **Attention:** The DMN is involved in attention, which is the ability to focus on a particular thing.
* **Emotion:** The DMN is involved in emotion, such as processing emotions and regulating emotional responses.
* **Decision-making:** The DMN is involved in decision-making, which is the process of choosing between different options.

name: Calcarine Sulcus
description: The calcarine sulcus is a deep groove on the medial surface of the occipital lobe of the brain. It is the primary visual cortex, which means that it is responsible for processing visual information.

name: Subthalamic Nucleus
description: The subthalamic nucleus (STN) is a small, egg-shaped structure located in the basal ganglia, a group of structures deep in the brain that are involved in movement control. The STN receives input from the globus pallidus, another structure in the basal ganglia, and it sends output to the substantia nigra, a structure in the midbrain.

name: Flocculonodular Lobe
description: The flocculonodular lobe, also known as the archicerebellum, is a small lobe at the back of the brain that is involved in balance and coordination. It is connected to the vestibular system, which is a sensory system that helps us maintain balance and spatial orientation.

name: Primary Motor Cortex
description: The primary motor cortex (M1) is a region of the brain that is responsible for planning and executing voluntary movements. It is located in the frontal lobe, just in front of the central sulcus.

name: Inferior Colliculus
description: The inferior colliculus (IC) is a structure in the midbrain that is involved in the processing of sound. It is part of the auditory pathway, which is the pathway that sound travels through the brain.

name: Occipital Lobe
description: The occipital lobe is the most posterior lobe of the brain, and it is responsible for processing visual information. It is located at the back of the head, and it is separated from the parietal lobe by the parieto-occipital sulcus.

name: Precentral Gyrus
description: The precentral gyrus is a strip of cortex located in the frontal lobe of the brain. It is responsible for planning and executing voluntary movements. It is also known as the primary motor cortex or Brodmann area 4.

name: Pituitary Stalk
description: The pituitary stalk is a small, slender stalk that connects the pituitary gland to the hypothalamus. It is about 10 millimeters long and 1 millimeter thick.

name: Parietal Lobe
description:
The parietal lobe is one of the four major lobes of the cerebral cortex, located in the upper part of the brain. It is responsible for a variety of functions, including:

* **Somatosensory perception:** The parietal lobe receives sensory information from the body, such as touch, pain, temperature, and proprioception (the sense of body position).
* **Spatial awareness:** The parietal lobe helps us to understand our surroundings and to navigate through space.
* **Language:** The parietal lobe is involved in some aspects of language, such as understanding the meaning of words and sentences.

name: Cingulate Gyrus
description: The cingulate gyrus is a large, curved band of cortex that runs along the medial surface of the cerebral hemispheres. It is part of the limbic system, which is a group of brain structures that are involved in emotions, motivation, and memory.

name: Pituitary Gland
description: The pituitary gland, also known as the hypophysis, is a small, pea-sized gland located at the base of the brain. It is attached to the hypothalamus by a thin stalk. The pituitary gland is responsible for producing and releasing hormones that control many important functions in the body, including growth, reproduction, and metabolism.

name: Ventral Anterior Nucleus
description:
The ventral anterior nucleus (VA) is a nucleus in the thalamus, a group of nuclei deep in the brain that are involved in relaying sensory information to the cortex and in controlling movement. The VA is involved in a variety of functions, including:

* **Initiating and planning movements:** The VA is involved in the initiation and planning of voluntary movements.
* **Motivation:** The VA is involved in motivation, such as the desire to eat, drink, and have sex.
* **Emotion:** The VA is involved in emotion, such as the experience of pleasure and pain.

name: Broca’s Area
description: Broca's area is a region of the brain that is involved in speech production. It is located in the frontal lobe, on the left side of the brain, and is named after Pierre Paul Broca, the French surgeon who first identified it in 1861.

name: Parahippocampal Gyrus
description: The parahippocampal gyrus is a region of the brain that is involved in memory and navigation. It is located in the temporal lobe, on the medial side of the brain, and is named after its proximity to the hippocampus.

name: Prefrontal Cortex
description:
The prefrontal cortex (PFC) is a region of the brain that is involved in a wide range of functions, including:

* **Executive functions:** The PFC is involved in executive functions, such as planning, decision-making, and problem-solving.
* **Social behavior:** The PFC is involved in social behavior, such as understanding the emotions of others and responding appropriately.
* **Working memory:** The PFC is involved in working memory, which is the ability to hold information in mind and manipulate it.
* **Emotion:** The PFC is involved in emotion, such as regulating emotions and understanding the emotional states of others.

name: Cerebellar Hemisphere
description: The cerebellar hemisphere is one of the two halves of the cerebellum, a large, paired structure at the back of the brain. It is responsible for coordinating movement, balance, and posture.

name: Hippocampus
description:
The hippocampus is a small, seahorse-shaped structure located in the temporal lobe of the brain. It is involved in a number of functions, including:

* **Long-term memory:** The hippocampus is involved in the formation of long-term memories, such as memories of events and places.
* **Spatial navigation:** The hippocampus is involved in spatial navigation, such as the ability to find your way around a familiar environment.
* **Emotion:** The hippocampus is involved in emotion, such as the experience of fear and anxiety.

name: Substantia Nigra
description:
The substantia nigra is a small, dark-colored nucleus located in the midbrain. It is involved in a number of functions, including:

* **Movement:** The substantia nigra is involved in the control of movement, such as the initiation and coordination of voluntary movements.
* **Reward:** The substantia nigra is involved in the reward system, which is responsible for the experience of pleasure.
* **Learning:** The substantia nigra is involved in learning, such as the ability to learn new skills.

name: Inferior Cerebellar Peduncles
description: The inferior cerebellar peduncles (ICPs) are a pair of bundles of nerve fibers that connect the cerebellum to the brainstem. They are responsible for carrying information from the spinal cord and brainstem to the cerebellum, and from the cerebellum to the spinal cord.

name: Ventral Posteromedial Nucleus
description: The ventral posteromedial nucleus (VPM) is a nucleus in the thalamus that receives sensory information from the face and head. It is responsible for relaying this information to the somatosensory cortex, which is responsible for processing touch, pain, temperature, and other sensory information from the body.

name: Subiculum
description: The subiculum is a part of the hippocampus, a structure in the brain that is involved in memory and spatial navigation. The subiculum is located in the medial temporal lobe, and it is thought to be involved in the consolidation of memories from short-term to long-term storage.

name: Corona Radiata
description: The corona radiata is a white matter tract in the brain that connects the cerebral cortex to the thalamus and other subcortical structures. It is a sheet of nerve fibers that radiates outward from the cortex, like the spokes of a wheel.

name: Dentate Nucleus
description: The dentate nucleus is a part of the cerebellum, a structure in the brain that is involved in motor control, balance, and coordination. The dentate nucleus is located in the medial temporal lobe, and it is thought to be involved in the planning and execution of movements.

name: Hippocampus Proper
description: The hippocampus proper is the main part of the hippocampus, a structure in the brain that is involved in memory and spatial navigation. The hippocampus proper is located in the medial temporal lobe, and it is thought to be involved in the consolidation of memories from short-term to long-term storage.
